Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(). Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard
the core and seeds, thinly slice then chop into 1cm chunks. Finely chop the
@flat leaf parsley{1}(chopped) (stalks and all!). Quarter the @dried apricots{40}.
Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #saucepan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil
is really hot, add the red pepper and fry until starting to char, ~{4-5%minutes}.
Only stir 3-4 times so they get nicely coloured. Remove them to a #bowl{}, and pop
your pan back on medium-high heat. Add another drizzle of @oil{drizzle} and add
the red onion. Cook, stirring frequently until the onion is really nicely softened
and golden, ~{5-6%minutes}, reduce the heat if necessary.

Pour the @water for the bulgur wheat{150%ml}(see ingredients for amount) into the
saucepan with the onion and bring to the boil. Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g},
red pepper and @chicken stock powder{1}. Bring back up to the boil and simmer for
~{1%minute}, then pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the
side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #large saucepan{} on medium heat.
Add the garlic, @chermoula spice mix{1} and @tomato puree{30%g}, stir and cook for
~{1%minute}. Then stir in the @water for the sauce{150%ml}(see ingredients for amount),
apricots and the @red wine stock paste{14}. Bring to a boil, stirring to dissolve
the stock, and then add the @lamb shank{670%g} and all of the juices in the bag.
Baste the lamb in the liquid using a #large spoon{} and lower the heat to a simmer.

Simmer (uncovered) and baste the lamb occasionally until the sauce reduces and is
thick and tomatoey, ~{15-20%minutes}. Increase the heat if the sauce isn't reducing.
Whilst the lamb cooks, quickly do any washing up. Once cooked, taste and add
@salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} if you feel it needs it.

> IMPORTANT: The lamb is cooked when piping hot all the way through.

Once the lamb is cooked, fluff up the bulgur wheat with a #fork{} and stir in half
the parsley. Spoon into #bowls{}. Use a #slotted spoon{} to take the lamb out of
the sauce and place on top of the bulgur wheat. Spoon the sauce over the lamb and
finish with a sprinkle of parsley and @dukkah mix{1}. Enjoy!